<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-527-536  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 527 536.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Industrial Computing  May 1990 p21(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Engineering database management. (includes related articles on EDMand EDM products)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lawrence, Andy.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Engineering data management (EDM) attempts to impose a managementcontrol system onto existing manufacturing systems and databasesin order to harness them together and make them more effective.andO;Research indicates European EDM implementations could grow to 90million pounds sterling by 1993.andP;  EDM attempts to make relevantdesign data more accessible, facilitate locating and retrievingdesign and engineering data, manage design changes moreeffectively, and solve problems caused by companies' use ofdifferent computer systems and data storage formats.andP;  Most EDMsoftware attempts to bridge the gap between design and productionwith an extended CAD database, extend the production planningsystem back into design, and use a process planning database.andP;  EDMsystems can be expensive and difficult to implement, however.andO;They require total corporate commitment in order to succeed, butcompanies are wary to make such a commitment.andP;  EDM requirescompromises and changes to existing manual procedures, and many ofits technical problems remain to be solved.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     EngineeringData ManagementTrendsSystem DesignEuropeData Base Management Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Engineering data management multilevel functionality. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>